From: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
Subject: [PATCH] ath11k: keep copy engine access off the Q6 while it is down

On the AHB bus (IPQ8074) the WLAN copy engine register space is only
accessible while the Q6 subsystem is powered; a read while TrustZone is
tearing the subsystem down or bringing it back up raises a synchronous
external abort in interrupt context and takes the whole SoC down.
Observed on IPQ8074 during firmware recovery:

  ath11k_ahb_ce_interrupt_handler
    ath11k_ahb_ce_irq_disable        <- CE register read
  (__scm_smc_call for the wcss stop concurrent on another CPU)

Two paths reach CE registers inside that window:

1. ath11k_core_reset() calls ath11k_hif_ce_irq_disable() before
   ath11k_hif_power_down(), but the plain AHB hif ops do not implement
   the ce_irq_enable/ce_irq_disable pair, so the copy engine interrupts
   stay live across rproc_shutdown(). Implement the ops: mask the CE
   interrupt-enable bits while the target is still powered, then wait
   out in-flight handlers and tasklets - the same sequence the PCI bus
   uses in ath11k_pcic_ce_irq_disable_sync() and ath11k_ahb_stop()
   already uses on the shutdown path. ath11k_ahb_start() re-enables the
   interrupts once the recovered firmware is up.

2. When the firmware crashes, the remoteproc core stops the Q6 on its
   own schedule, tens of milliseconds after the fatal-error IRQ and
   while the just-crashed firmware's final burst of CE interrupts is
   still being serviced - the driver gets no say in that ordering.
   Gate the CE interrupt handler and tasklet on the remoteproc state:
   it is moved off RPROC_RUNNING before the TrustZone teardown starts
   and moved back only after the subsystem is powered up again. The CE
   interrupts are edge triggered, so a skipped event cannot storm, and
   the recovery path reprograms the rings from scratch anyway.

Signed-off-by: Julius Bairaktaris <julius@bairaktaris.de>
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath11k/ahb.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath11k/ahb.c
@@ -374,6 +374,13 @@ static void ath11k_ahb_ce_irqs_disable(s
 	}
 }
 
+static void ath11k_ahb_ce_irq_disable_sync(struct ath11k_base *ab)
+{
+	ath11k_ahb_ce_irqs_disable(ab);
+	ath11k_ahb_sync_ce_irqs(ab);
+	ath11k_ahb_kill_tasklets(ab);
+}
+
 static int ath11k_ahb_start(struct ath11k_base *ab)
 {
 	ath11k_ahb_ce_irqs_enable(ab);
@@ -481,6 +488,10 @@ static void ath11k_ahb_free_irq(struct a
 static void ath11k_ahb_ce_tasklet(struct tasklet_struct *t)
 {
 	struct ath11k_ce_pipe *ce_pipe = from_tasklet(ce_pipe, t, intr_tq);
+	struct ath11k_ahb *ab_ahb = ath11k_ahb_priv(ce_pipe->ab);
+
+	if (ab_ahb->tgt_rproc->state != RPROC_RUNNING)
+		return;
 
 	ath11k_ce_per_engine_service(ce_pipe->ab, ce_pipe->pipe_num);
 
@@ -490,6 +501,15 @@ static void ath11k_ahb_ce_tasklet(struct
 static irqreturn_t ath11k_ahb_ce_interrupt_handler(int irq, void *arg)
 {
 	struct ath11k_ce_pipe *ce_pipe = arg;
+	struct ath11k_ahb *ab_ahb = ath11k_ahb_priv(ce_pipe->ab);
+
+	/* While the Q6 is stopped or booting, the WLAN CE register space
+	 * is not accessible; a read raises a synchronous external abort.
+	 * The remoteproc core marks the state before it starts the
+	 * TrustZone teardown, so skip the (edge triggered) interrupt.
+	 */
+	if (ab_ahb->tgt_rproc->state != RPROC_RUNNING)
+		return IRQ_HANDLED;
 
 	/* last interrupt received for this CE */
 	ce_pipe->timestamp = jiffies;
@@ -811,6 +831,8 @@ static const struct ath11k_hif_ops ath11
 	.map_service_to_pipe = ath11k_ahb_map_service_to_pipe,
 	.power_down = ath11k_ahb_power_down,
 	.power_up = ath11k_ahb_power_up,
+	.ce_irq_enable = ath11k_ahb_ce_irqs_enable,
+	.ce_irq_disable = ath11k_ahb_ce_irq_disable_sync,
 };
 
 static const struct ath11k_hif_ops ath11k_ahb_hif_ops_wcn6750 = {
